name: Whitcomb KinderCare
introduction: Even after school's out for the day, children need to be engaged in a comfortable, yet stimulating environment. That's where our Catch the Wave® program comes in. From homework help to fun physical activities, our program is designed so that everyone goes home happy.

name: Boys & Girls Clubs of Greater Kansas City - Olathe Unit
hoursopen: School Year Hours: Before School: 6:30am - 8:30am, After School:  2:00pm - 7:00pm; Full Day Program: 7:00am - 6:00pm
introduction: The Boys & Girls Clubs of Greater Kansas City inspires kids to live out their dreams by providing affordable, accessible opportunities in the urban core. Thanks to our generous supporters, nearly 8,000 local kids get to experience “luxuries” they never thought possible. Baseball games. Private tutors. Art classes. Fieldtrips. And more. By simply joining the Club, the youth of Kansas City are already taking a step towards a GREAT future.
pricing: Membership for one full school year is only $15

name: Boys & Girls Clubs of South Central Kansas - Oaklawn Club
introduction: BE GREAT is an idea that within every child there is the potential for greatness and all of us play a vital role in helping young people find and achieve their dreams. Boys & Girls Clubs encourages all kids to BE GREAT by nurturing their self-esteem through instilling in them a sense of belonging, competence, power and influence, and usefulness. The Boys & Girls Clubs of South Central Kansas does this daily by providing young people with caring adult professionals and fun, age-appropriate, well-rounded programming. The club has been giving kids a better chance against problems such as gangs, street violence and juvenile crime since 1990.

name: Boys & Girls Club of Manhattan - 5th Street Unit
introduction: The Boys & Girls Club of Manhattan provides a compelling alternative to youth crime, drugs and other negative influences that affect our youth today. It is a safe place that kids can call their "own" where qualified staff and caring volunteers give members the opportunity to: Enjoy their interests; Nurture their talents; Discover their personality; Develop friendships; Build self-esteem; Contribute to society; Achieve personal success

name: Boys & Girls Club of Atchison
hoursopen: School Year: Mon - Thurs: After school - 6:00pm, Fri: After school - 5:00pm; Summer Hours: 8:45am - 1:30pm
introduction: If you are looking for a safe, fun, and affordable environment for your school aged children, you have come to the right place! Located near the corner of Ash and M Streets in Atchison, our club stands ready to offer your child a wide range of activities to participate in ranging from physical to academic. Different programs also offer them the chance to give back to community and learn important life skills.
pricing: Membership fees are just $10 a month for the first child in a family, and $5 for each additional child, and are due on the first Monday of each month Reduced fees are available for those families that qualify.

name: Ascension Y Club
introduction: With a focus on safety, health, social growth and academic enhancement, Y Club before and after school gives kindergartners through sixth graders a safe, supportive and fun environment to learn, develop interests and make friends. Parents enjoy the convenience of a state licensed program in their child's school, affordable weekly fees, and peace of mind knowing that qualified, trained staff are there to provide a positive atmosphere.

name: Garden City Family YMCA Before School/After School @ Abe Hubert Elementary School
introduction: Since 1964, the YMCA has been serving Finney County and the surrounding communities behind the foresight of three gentlemen; Clifford Mayo, Bryce Roderick Sr and Carlos C. Spikes. The YMCA was blessed back then by our founding fathers and today we are fortunate to have the community support our non-profit organization. Being a membership and program-driven organization, we rely on volunteers and contributions to help support our mission. From our first campaign of $300,000 to build the YMCA to our very latest Capital Campaign of over $2 million, this YMCA is built from donors, friends and foundations who believe in our mission! This is pretty awesome.
pricing: Before School - $16/wk; After School - $8/wk; Equipment Fee: $10

introduction: Since 1964, the YMCA has been serving Finney County and the surrounding communities behind the foresight of three gentlemen; Clifford Mayo, Bryce Roderick Sr and Carlos C. Spikes. The YMCA was blessed back then by our founding fathers and today we are fortunate to have the community support our non-profit organization. Being a membership and program-driven organization, we rely on volunteers and contributions to help support our mission. From our first campaign of $300,000 to build the YMCA to our very latest Capital Campaign of over $2 million, this YMCA is built from donors, friends and foundations who believe in our mission! This is pretty awesome.
pricing: Before School - $16/wk; After School - $16/wk; Equipment Fee: $20

name: Girls on the Run Kansas City @ Blue River Elementary
introduction: Girls on the Run began in Kansas City in 2007. Initially, two councils existed - Girls on the Run of Johnson County and Girls on the Run of Jackson County. In 2012, seeking to combine resources and expand the program to reach the maximum number of girls in the Kansas City area, the Board of Directors of both organizations voted unanimously to combine the councils. On July 1, 2012, Girls on the Run Serving Greater Kansas City was established. Girls on the Run Serving Greater Kansas City serves over 4,000 girls ages 8-13 years old each year. Our program sites are located at more than 115 different schools and community centers in 15 counties throughout the Kansas City metropolitan area.

name: Girls on the Run Heart of Kansas @ Anderson Elementary

name: Girls on the Run Northeast Kansas @ Berryton Elementary
introduction: Over a period of 12 weeks, girls in the 3rd through 5th grade participate in an after-school program like no other. Designed to allow every girl to recognize her inner strength, the Girls on the Run curriculum inspires girls to define their lives on their own terms. Throughout the season, the girls make new friends, build their confidence and celebrate all that makes them unique. We are very excited for the release of our new middle school curriculum, Heart & Sole, in fall of 2015.  The Heart & Sole curriculum was developed to meet the unique needs of middle school girls by focusing on the whole girl. The curriculum is designed with themes girls can relate to and helps build the life skills they need. Heart & Sole is accessible to all girls regardless of athletic ability or fitness level and considers the age range and varied experiences of middle schoolers.
pricing: The GOTR program fee is $150. Registration fees help us fulfill our commitment to provide every girl with an outstanding experience. Financial assistance is available to qualifying families unable to pay the full fee. We ask for your commitment to providing accurate information about your family’s financial status.

name: Girls on the Run Northeast Kansas @ Elmont Elementary
introduction: Over a period of 12 weeks, girls in the 3rd through 5th grade participate in an after-school program like no other. Designed to allow every girl to recognize her inner strength, the Girls on the Run curriculum inspires girls to define their lives on their own terms. Throughout the season, the girls make new friends, build their confidence and celebrate all that makes them unique. The Girls on the Run lessons encourage positive emotional, social, mental and physical development.  Participants explore and discuss their own beliefs around experiences and challenges girls face at this age.  They also develop important strategies and skills to help them navigate life experiences. We start with helping the girls get a better understanding of who they are and what’s important to them.  Then, we look at the importance of team work and healthy relationships.  And, finally, the girls explore how they can positively connect with and shape the world. Physical activity is woven into our program to inspire an appreciation of fitness and to build habits that lead to a lifetime of health.  At the end of each three month session, the girls participate in a Girls on the Run 5k event.  This celebratory, non-competitive event is the culminating experience of the curriculum.  Completing the 5k gives the girls a tangible understanding of the confidence that comes through accomplishment as well as a framework for setting and achieving life goals.  Crossing the finish line is a defining moment when the girls realize that even the seemingly impossible IS possible.
pricing: The GOTR program fee is $150. Registration fees help us fulfill our commitment to provide every girl with an outstanding experience. Financial assistance is available to qualifying families unable to pay the full fee. We ask for your commitment to providing accurate information about your family’s financial status.

The curriculum is designed with themes girls can relate to and helps build the life skills they need. name: Girls on the Run Northeast Kansas @ Pauline Central Elementary
introduction: Over a period of 12 weeks, girls in the 3rd through 5th grade participate in an after-school program like no other. Designed to allow every girl to recognize her inner strength, the Girls on the Run curriculum inspires girls to define their lives on their own terms. Throughout the season, the girls make new friends, build their confidence and celebrate all that makes them unique. The Girls on the Run lessons encourage positive emotional, social, mental and physical development.  Participants explore and discuss their own beliefs around experiences and challenges girls face at this age.  They also develop important strategies and skills to help them navigate life experiences. We start with helping the girls get a better understanding of who they are and what’s important to them.  Then, we look at the importance of team work and healthy relationships.  And, finally, the girls explore how they can positively connect with and shape the world. Physical activity is woven into our program to inspire an appreciation of fitness and to build habits that lead to a lifetime of health.  At the end of each three month session, the girls participate in a Girls on the Run 5k event.  This celebratory, non-competitive event is the culminating experience of the curriculum.  Completing the 5k gives the girls a tangible understanding of the confidence that comes through accomplishment as well as a framework for setting and achieving life goals.  Crossing the finish line is a defining moment when the girls realize that even the seemingly impossible IS possible.
pricing: The GOTR program fee is $150. Registration fees help us fulfill our commitment to provide every girl with an outstanding experience. name: Master Overbey's Martial Arts - After School Karate Program
introduction: A Fun, Structured, Supervised Program for Your Children That Teaches Them Confidence, Pride & Respect. Children & their parents absolutely love our program. After all, every moment is packed with fun, engaging activities that teach your kids the skills they need for success in life.

name: CGS After School Program
introduction: The vision for the CGS After School Program is to broaden learning horizons for K-5 youth through high quality academic and life skills experiences. The learning will be facilitated by technology in a safe and caring environment. This program will run Monday-Thursday after school until 5:30 p.m. at Colby Grade School. Students may be enrolled on a regular basis for each day, specified days, or occasional days. Academics, wellness, and enrichment will be a part of each day. The program will offer nutritious snacks and activities to promote health and wellness. Certified teachers and paraprofessionals will support and enhance academics in a technology rich environment by tutoring, providing homework assistance, and extending learning designed to meet each child’s needs. Educational enrichment sessions such as drama, art, music/dance, martial arts, and Lego robotics are just a few activities that will be a fun and exciting part of the program.
pricing: Free lunch status students -no charge, Reduced lunch status students - $20.00, Non-Free lunch/Reduced lunch Students - $45.00

name: Tiger Trails After School Program @ Sullivan Elementary
introduction: The program runs from 3:45-5:30 pm. This year we will be hitting the academics hard and playing even harder than last year. Enrichments will be focused in the following areas: Arts and Crafts, Career Exploration, Cultural, Health/Wellness and Character Building. We will be taking the kids to the swimming pool. We are planning for the best year ever with the program. The program is open to all students in Primary thru 5th grade. We do offer a shuttle bus between the schools.

name: Tiger Trails After School Program @ Hickok Elementary
introduction: The program runs from 3:45-5:30 pm. This year we will be hitting the academics hard and playing even harder than last year. name: KRR (HES After School Program)
introduction: Hugoton Elementary School was awarded this KRR grant in May 2014. This grant has four components to ensure that your child can reach their full reading potential by third grade. The components are summer school, in-school, after-school, and out­of­school. The programs are offered to families with children in grades kindergarten through third grade. The needs are based on testing that is implemented by the classroom teachers throughout the year. The after school program is offered Monday through Thursday after school from 3:30­5:00 pm. Students are referred by their teachers based on the continued needs of the in­school MTSS. The ASP is for children that need tutoring in reading only. There is no math component or homework help. The program is designed to help students read on­grade level by the end of third grade

name: LEAP (HES After School Program)
introduction: L.E.A.P. is a 21st Century CCLC five-year federal grant. L.E.A.P. will serve Kindergarten through 6th grade students. In addition to getting a healthy snack and recess each day, all students will receive homework help, tutoring, and supplemental academic activities. Once a week each grade will rotate through a structured enrichment activity; which will focus on science, technology, engineering, art, and math.

name: USD 350 LIFE (Learning is Fun Enrichment) After-School Program
introduction: USD 350's LIFE (Learning is Fun Enrichment) After-School Program is open to any current USD 350 student, providing K-12 academic support, tutoring and non-formal enrichment programs. The LIFE program is made possible by a 21st CCLC grant. The mission of the LIFE After-School Program is to provide a safe and affordable, structured, extended school day for the enrichment of all K-12 students. In addition to a snack and physical activity (K-6), we focus on the following areas: Fine Arts (Arts and Crafts, Music); Health/Nutrition; Character Education; Life/Social Skills; Technology; Community Service; Drug Prevention/Awareness; Career Planning (9-12); General Academics/Tutoring (K-12)

name: STARS After School
introduction: STARS "Shining Through Academics and Relationships at Stafford" After School offers hands-on learning activities every school day from 3:15 - 5:30 pm for all students in Grades K-8 in the USD 349.

name: Fowler Aspire 4 Higher
EXITO After School Program @ Comanche Middle School
introduction: The EXITO After School Program is designed for secondary students in grades 6-12 at Dodge City Middle School, Comanche Middle School, and Dodge City High School. Students will engage in enrichment opportunities, homework assistance, skill building activities, language acquisition, and career path options. From these extended learning opportunities we expect our students to increase their achievement scores in reading and math, discover career interests and opportunities, and build relationships with other students and staff.

name: Haysville S.P.A.R.K. Program
introduction: S.P.A.R.K. is a before and afterschool program available to Middle School students in Haysville USD 261. We offer our students: homework and tutoring assistance; sports and recreation; arts and crafts; performing arts; service learning and leadership opportunities; field trips; social events; guest speakers; use of ipads, laptops, and computers; game room with ping pong, air hockey, pool, video games and Pac-Man Arcade machine; snack each day.
pricing: Before School  Program $75 year, Early Bird Discount: $60 if enrolled and paid by Sept 29; After School Program: $150 year, Early Bird Discount: $140 if enrolled and paid by Sept 29. Combo Discount (HMS only): $200 for both programs. Must sign up for Before and After School Programs at the same time to get the discount.

name: Hilltop Child Development Center School-Age Program
introduction: Hilltop offers school-age programs at the Hilltop site at 1605 Irving Hill Road on the KU campus. Each site has a Lead Teacher and Assistant Teacher who offer arts and crafts, dramatic play, music, table games, science and social studies projects, manipulatives, books, puzzles, sports and daily outdoor play. Our goal is to provide safe, high-quality care and activities that are fun and relaxing as well as educational. All enrollments are for five days a week. The Jayhawk and Bobcat Rooms offer an after-school program for K through 5th grades. Van pick-up is offered from many schools. Children are picked up earlier on public school early dismissal days. Afternoon snack is provided. A full-day option is available in the summer. Ratio is 1 adult per 14 children with a total of 28 children in the Jayhawk Room and 28 children in the Bobcat Room.
pricing: There is a non-refundable application fee of $25 for KU Student families and $35 for all other families and a $350 deposit payable upon acceptance.

name: Xcel After-School Program
introduction: Our Mission: Help students recognize the unlimited possibilities that lie before them, believe in their ability to do great things, succeed in the important relationships of their lives, and make a difference in their world.

name: Trinity United Methodist Church Backpack Connection
introduction: FREE after school program for children in 1st through 5th grade.  The program includes homework session, games, crafts, science, music, drama, and bible stories.  Backpack Connection begins on September 14 and then every Thursday school is in session through April 26. Times are 3:30 to 5:15 PM. Transportation to Trinity UMC at 3:30 PM will be available through OCCK bus services or private vehicle from Schilling, Grace E. Stewart and Coronado schools.

name: WASP @ Eisenhower Elementary
introduction: The daily program offers the following activities: Homework Assistance; Arts & crafts, visual arts; Hands-on activities; Indoor/outdoor activities; Physical fitness/health/wellness; Recess and snack time 3:30 to 4:00 pm; Monthly calendar will reflect program activities.

name: Bergman Learning in After School Time (BLAST)
introduction: The Bergman Learning in After School Time (BLAST) program serves students enrolled at Bergman, and is primarily designed for those whom a structured, supervised before and after-school program can provide. The before school program welcomes students as early as 7:00am. This aspect of the program provides all students with the opportunity for supervised physical activities under the guidance of supervisors until students go to classrooms at 8:30am. The afterschool activities begin at 3:40pm, and focus on enrichment activities in science, technology engineering and math (STEM). Students that are qualified to ride a USD383 bus can be bused home from BLAST at 5:30 p.m.. Students who are not bused must be picked up before 6:00 p.m.
pricing: Mornings Only: $85.00/month per student; Afternoons Only: Sliding fee schedule per student from $30.00 - $150.00 monthly, depending on total gross household income; Mornings & Afternoons: Sliding fee schedule per student from $45.00 - $165.00 monthly, depending on total gross household income. Out-of-school days: $25.00 for students currently enrolled in BLAST; $35 for all other Bergman students

name: Panther Power Club
introduction: We strive to offer programming that will interest your child and help him/her academically, socially, and physically.

name: Neodesha After School Program
introduction: Neodesha After School Program begin in August 2016. It is funded through a 21st Century Community Learning Center Grant with additional assistance of several local community partners.

name: Kids CREW
introduction: Kids CREW is an after school program designed to provide extended academic and enrichment opportunities beyond the regular school day in a fun, structured and safe environment. Enrollment is open to students enrolled in Kindergarten through sixth grade. Kids CREW is staffed by certified teachers, paraprofessionals, classroom aides and tutors.
pricing: The regular Kids CREW fee is $25 weekly regardless of the number of days your child is in attendance. If you have multiple children from the same household enrolled in Kids CREW, $25 a week will be charged for the first child, and a discounted price of $15 a week will be charged for each additional child.  Students enrolled in the Four County Quest Program can attend Kids CREW for $5 a day when Quest is not in session.

name: USD 250 After School Care @ George Nettels Elementary
introduction: USD 250 values a safe and enriched environment for students during out of school time. After school care is offered by the district as a resource to help meet the diverse needs of USD 250 families. This programming further enhances the use of district staff and facility resources.

name: The Learning Club of KCK @ Blessed Sacrament
introduction: Learning Club serves over 120 children in Kansas City, Kansas, meeting once or twice a week at each of our five sites. Our students are primarily in the 1st to 6th grades, though some are older. During the school year, we focus on homework help with one-on-one volunteer tutors, as well as enrichment programs and educational field trips. In all of our activities, we teach manners, cooperation, and character development. During the summer, when over 85% of our students have no other activities in which to participate, we provide extra programming, creating opportunities to keep our students’ minds sharp and their time productively occupied. All of our programs are completely free for the students. Our attendance rates and retention rates are excellent. Students love the one-on-one attention of a caring adult, as well as the healthy snacks that we provide each session. Students are also motivated by earning points for their academic achievement and for arriving on time. With their points, they can buy prizes ranging from basic school supplies to a new bike. Students who save their points instead of buying a prize are rewarded with interest points, teaching them the value of saving and resisting immediate gratification.Our staff and volunteers strive to work with parents and teachers of the children to meet their educational and behavioral needs. Most parents and teachers report remarkable progress by the students since beginning the Learning Club. In addition to academic work, students enjoy enrichment programs led by people from the community who teach art, healthy eating, public speaking, career exploration, and many other topics. Field trips to places like the Kansas City Symphony, the Discovery Center, and the Deanna Rose Children’s Farm have helped to broaden the horizons of our students, most of whom have had little exposure to such experiences.

name: The Learning Club of KCK @ Chalet Manor
introduction: Learning Club serves over 120 children in Kansas City, Kansas, meeting once or twice a week at each of our five sites. Our students are primarily in the 1st to 6th grades, though some are older. During the school year, we focus on homework help with one-on-one volunteer tutors, as well as enrichment programs and educational field trips. In all of our activities, we teach manners, cooperation, and character development. During the summer, when over 85% of our students have no other activities in which to participate, we provide extra programming, creating opportunities to keep our students’ minds sharp and their time productively occupied. All of our programs are completely free for the students. Our attendance rates and retention rates are excellent. Students love the one-on-one attention of a caring adult, as well as the healthy snacks that we provide each session. Students are also motivated by earning points for their academic achievement and for arriving on time. With their points, they can buy prizes ranging from basic school supplies to a new bike. Students who save their points instead of buying a prize are rewarded with interest points, teaching them the value of saving and resisting immediate gratification.Our staff and volunteers strive to work with parents and teachers of the children to meet their educational and behavioral needs. Most parents and teachers report remarkable progress by the students since beginning the Learning Club. In addition to academic work, students enjoy enrichment programs led by people from the community who teach art, healthy eating, public speaking, career exploration, and many other topics. Field trips to places like the Kansas City Symphony, the Discovery Center, and the Deanna Rose Children’s Farm have helped to broaden the horizons of our students, most of whom have had little exposure to such experiences.

name: Boys & Girls Clubs of Kentuckiana - Bullitt Lick Site
introduction: Boys & Girls Clubs of Kentuckiana (BGCK) is an out-of-school time provider, offering a safe haven for youth who need us. We open our doors and our arms to kids ages 6-18, in a safe, positive environment. Inside our Clubs, kids are greeted by name by adult youth professionals in a fun, family atmosphere. We encourage the development of the whole child by focusing on 3 priority outcome areas: Academic Success, Good Character & Citizenship and Healthy Lifestyles. Click here to learn more about our programs. In addition, Boys & Girls Clubs of Kentuckiana operates Kids Cafes in each of its Clubs in partnership with the Dare to Care Food Bank, serving a hot meal every day.

name: Boys & Girls Club of Bowling Green
introduction: Our Mission: To enable all young people, especially those who need us most, to reach their full potential as productive, caring, responsible citizens.
pricing: The Fee is $25 for the school year and $200 for the Summer Program – scholarships are available.

name: Boys and Girls Club of Glasgow-Barren County
introduction: The Boys and Girls Club of Glasgow-Barren County offers a fun, safe place to grow and learn; a place filled with a variety of age appropriate programs, a full schedule of activities and numerous opportunities! The Club provides diversified activities that meet the interests of all young people through 5 core programs: Character and Leaderships Development, Education and Career Development, Health and Life Skills, The Arts and Sports, Fitness and Recreation. These programs help members with homework, encourage their involvement within our community, expose them ti a variety of sports and promote new interest in various hobbies.

name: Boys & Girls Club of Franklin-Simpson
hoursopen: School Session Hours: 3:00pm-7:00pm; Summer Hours (June-July): 8:00am-5:00pm; Spring & Fall Break Hours: 8:00am-4:00pm
introduction: The Boys & Girls Club of Franklin-Simpson is just one of 4,000 Boys & Girls Clubs across America. We are a group of organizations, all here for the same reason; to provide a fun, educational, safe place for children to go to reach their full potential. Here at the BGC of Franklin-Simpson, our children are dropped off from the buses right at our front door after school and we are open during school breaks and summer. We keep children off the streets and involved in activities that teach them how to succeed. Great futures start here each and every day!
pricing: The cost to join the Club is only $12.00 per child for the entire school year.

name: Tom Browning Boys & Girls Club
introduction: The Tom Browning Boys & Girls Club is a non-profit youth development organization dedicated to promoting health, physical, social, educational, vocational, cultural, character and leadership development. To inspire and enable all young people, especially those from disadvantage circumstances, to realize their full potential as productive, responsible and caring citizens. The Tom Browning Boys & Girls Club will be a leading provider of programs emphasizing youth development services to meet the needs of young people ages 5-15. We serve children ages 5-15, offering a tutoring program through the Mason County School System and St. Patrick’s School.

name: Harlan County Boys and Girls Club
introduction: Nearly 15 years ago, a group of concerned citizens- led by Tony & Tommie Saragas- joined together to form Harlan County Youth Sports, an organization devoted to providing positive sports leagues and activities to the children of Harlan County.  It didn't take long for this group to realize that the children of our area needed much more than sports.  They needed the opportunities that only a Boys & Girls Club could provide and in April 2003, the Harlan County Boys and Girls Club opened its first dedicated youth facility- The Cawood Ledford Boys & Girls Club- located at the former Loyall Elementary School.  In January 2005, the Club moved into a storefront facility in downtown Harlan and launched a massive capital campaign to raise funds to build a new facility. Led by architect Dwyne Wilkerson and trustees Rick Fox and Don Parsons, construction began on a new, permanent facility in June 2006. In August 2007, the newly constructed Cawood Ledford facility opened in the Fairview section of Harlan.  Named for Kentucky's legendary sports announcer, the Cawood Ledford Club is tailor-made for our members and offers a large game room, an arts and crafts room, a technology lab, a fitness room, an education lab, kitchen and administrative offices. Scores of children, from both county and city schools, take part in the life-changing programs offered in this facility each day.
pricing: Membership is only $25 per school year and it access to the club anytime it is open.

name: Boys & Girls Club of Butler County
Boys & Girls Clubs of Greater Cincinnati - Marge Schott-Unnewehr Club
introduction: Since 1939, the Boys & Girls Clubs of Greater Cincinnati has been changing lives and building great futures for kids who need a safe and positive place to spend the most vulnerable times of the day-immediately after school and at night, when supervision is often lacking and temptations are great. Our doors are open to the community’s youth, who are invited in to enrich their lives with Club membership, exceptional staff and volunteers, high-quality services and innovative programs, all at no cost. Every day, all of our kids do the things in this “home away from home” that will ultimately make a difference in their lives. They do their homework, and when they need help, we help them learn, grow and move forward with determination toward high school graduation and a plan for the future. They sit down together for a hot, nutritious meal, and learn about what to eat, how to cook and what to do to keep themselves healthy and fit for life. They serve each other in the Clubs and others in the community as they nurture the value of giving back. We are rightfully proud of our tradition and constantly work to build better, stronger homes in the Clubs so our kids can grow even brighter futures for themselves and for all of us. Because of our mission, history and vision for the future, BGCGC has become one of Cincinnati and Northern Kentucky’s strongest and most beloved youth service organizations. This is what we do, and this is who we are. Great futures start here.

name: Oscar Cross Boys and Girls Club of Paducah Inc.
introduction: OUR MISSION: To enable all young people, especially those who need us the most, to be all that they can be as productive, responsible and caring citizens.
pricing: Membership at the Club costs $10.00 per year.

name: Boys & Girls Club of Hopkinsville & Christian County
hoursopen: School Year: 2:30pm-6:30pm; School Break (Fall, Spring & Summer): 8:00am-5:30pm
introduction: In every community, boys and girls are left to find their own recreation and companionship in the streets. An increasing number of children are at home with no adult care or supervision. Young people need to know that someone cares about them. With the programs and positive influences we provide, the Boys and Girls Club is leading the way in youth development in Hopkinsville. Power Hour helps Club members be more successful in school by providing homework help and tutoring. SMART Moves helps young people resist alcohol, tobacco and other drug use. Meet & Greet connects our members with local professionals. Bud Hudson teaches the fundamentals of football, while instilling leadership and character in our young men. The Boys and Girls Club believes in the idea that within every child there is the potential for greatness. The Boys & Girls Club is a safe place to learn and grow - all while having fun.

name: Cliff Hagan Boys and Girls Club - Mike Horn Unit
introduction: In every community, boys and girls are left to find their own recreation and companionship in the streets. An increasing number of children are at home with no adult care or supervision. Young people need to know that someone cares about them. Our club programs and services promote and enhance the development of boys and girls 6-18 yrs of age by instilling a sense of competence, usefulness, belonging and influence.
